{
    command.Parameters.Add("@value1", DbType.String).Value = "foo";
    command.Parameters.Add("@value2", DbType.String).Value = "bar";
    // ...
```

2. Use a transaction to group multiple statements into a single unit of work. Example:

```
connection.Open();
using (SQLiteTransaction transaction = connection.BeginTransaction())
{
    try
    {
        // Execute multiple SQL queries here
        transaction.Commit();
    }
    catch
    {
        transaction.Rollback();
        throw;
    }
}
```

3. Cache the SQL command object for re-use. Example:

```
using (SQLiteCommand command = new SQLiteCommand())
{
    command.Connection = connection;
    command.CommandText = sql;
    command.Parameters.Add("@value1", DbType.String);
    command.Parameters.Add("@value2", DbType.String);

    // ...

