    .DefaultIndex("myindex");

var client = new ElasticClient(settings);

var searchResponse = client.Search<MyDocument>(s => s
    .Sort(sort => sort
        .Ascending(doc => doc.Timestamp))
    .SearchAfter(lastTimestamp) // Set the value of the last document from the previous page
    .Take(10) // Set the number of documents to retrieve for the current page
);

foreach (var hit in searchResponse.Hits)
{
    // Process search results
}
```

In this example, we're using the `Search` method of the `ElasticClient` object to perform the search. We're specifying that we want to sort the results by the `Timestamp` field in ascending order, and we're using the `SearchAfter` method to specify the value of the last document from the previous page. We're also using the `Take` method to specify the number of documents to retrieve for the current page (in this case, 10).

Once we've retrieved the search results, we can process them by iterating over the `Hits` property of the `searchResponse` object.

Note that in order to use the `SearchAfter` method, you'll need to ensure that your query includes a sort clause that uniquely identifies the documents being queried. In the example above, we're using the `Timestamp` field to sort the results, but you could use any other field that meets this criteria.

